*Assessment*

While testing EUCA-10993, used the following IAM access policy on Eucalyptus 4.2:
{code}
# cat euca10993-ec2-blank-policy.json
{
    "Version":"2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": "ec2:*",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:::instance/*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}
The comparable IAM access policy for AWS is as follows:
{code}
# cat euca10993-ec2-wildcard-policy.json
{
    "Version":"2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Action": "ec2:*",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:*:*:instance/*"
        }
    ]
}
{code}
The reason different IAM policies were used is due to EUCA-11223. 

_*AWS*_

When running tests on AWS, there are [a few EC2 actions supported when using a resource ARN containing a defined instance resource/resourcetype|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/ec2-supported-iam-actions-resources.html].  If any other EC2 action (e.g. DecribeInstances) is used, the following error will be displayed:
{code}
$ aws ec2 describe-instances --profile hasp-personal

A client error (UnauthorizedOperation) occurred when calling the DescribeInstances operation: You are not authorized to perform this operation.
{code}

_*Eucalyptus*_

On Eucalyptus 4.2, the user that has the applied IAM policy can run any action.
{code}
[root@h-08 ~]# euare-grouplistpolicies -g admins --region devops-admin@asap-rocky-2015 -v
